    rationale: "IgE IN ALLERGIC ASTHMA: (1) SENSITIZATION: Allergen exposure → dendritic cells present allergen → Th2 cells produce IL-4/IL-13 → B-cell class switching to IgE production → IgE enters circulation. (2) PRIMING: IgE binds high-affinity FcεRI receptors on mast cells (in airways) and basophils → mast cells are now 'armed.' (3) RE-EXPOSURE: Allergen cross-links 2+ IgE molecules on mast cell surface → FcεRI clustering → intracellular signaling cascade → DEGRANULATION. (4) MEDIATOR RELEASE: histamine (bronchospasm, vasodilation), prostaglandin D2, leukotriene C4/D4/E4 (potent bronchoconstrictors, 100-1000x more potent than histamine), platelet-activating factor. (5) LATE PHASE (4-8 hours): Cytokines recruit eosinophils → tissue damage, mucus hypersecretion. OMALIZUMAB: Humanized IgG1 mAb that binds the Cε3 domain on FREE circulating IgE. Critically, it CANNOT bind IgE already attached to FcεRI (same epitope is occupied) → no anaphylaxis risk from cross-linking surface-bound IgE. Effects: (a) Captures free IgE → reduces available IgE, (b) FcεRI expression DECREASES on mast cells/basophils over weeks (receptor expression is upregulated by IgE itself — remove IgE → receptors decline), (c) Long-term: reduced mast cell sensitivity to allergens. Dosing: based on baseline IgE level and body weight, SC q2-4 weeks.",
    explanationA: "IL-5 inhibition describes mepolizumab and reslizumab (anti-eosinophilic biologics). Omalizumab targets IgE, which plays a CENTRAL role in allergic asthma.",
