    rationale: "BUPRENORPHINE RECEPTOR PHARMACOLOGY: (1) PARTIAL μ-AGONIST: Binds μ-opioid receptor with VERY HIGH AFFINITY (Ki ~1 nM — higher than morphine, heroin, fentanyl) but activates the receptor to only ~40-60% of maximal efficacy (vs full agonists at ~100%). This creates a CEILING EFFECT: above ~16-32mg, increasing the dose produces NO additional respiratory depression or euphoria → SAFETY advantage over methadone (full agonist, no ceiling → overdose risk). (2) κ-ANTAGONIST: Blocks kappa-opioid receptors → may contribute to anti-dysphoria and antidepressant effects. (3) NOCICEPTIN (ORL-1) PARTIAL AGONIST: May contribute to analgesic properties. PRECIPITATED WITHDRAWAL MECHANISM: Patient on heroin (full agonist): μ-receptors are occupied with full activation → dependent neurons adapted to this. Buprenorphine introduced while heroin present: buprenorphine has HIGHER AFFINITY → DISPLACES heroin from receptor binding sites → BUT provides only PARTIAL activation → NET DECREASE in μ-receptor signaling (from ~100% with heroin to ~40-60% with buprenorphine) → experienced as ACUTE WITHDRAWAL (identical to naloxone-precipitated withdrawal but longer-lasting due to buprenorphine's long receptor residence time). INDUCTION PROTOCOL: Wait until patient is in MODERATE withdrawal (COWS ≥8-12) → sufficient heroin has cleared from receptors → buprenorphine's partial agonism provides NET IMPROVEMENT over the withdrawal state. Start: 2-4mg SL, observe 1-2 hours, titrate to 8-16mg on day 1. Target maintenance: 16-24mg daily. NALOXONE COMPONENT (naloxone in Suboxone): Included to DETER IV diversion — naloxone has poor sublingual bioavailability (~3-5%) → clinically inactive when taken sublingually as directed. If dissolved and injected → naloxone becomes bioavailable → precipitates withdrawal → deters misuse.",
    explanationA: "Buprenorphine is a PARTIAL agonist, NOT a full agonist. Methadone is the full μ-agonist MAT option. Premature induction withdrawal is from receptor-level displacement (partial replacing full agonism), not CYP interactions.",
    explanationB: "Correct. High-affinity partial μ-agonist displaces full agonists → net reduction in receptor activation → precipitated withdrawal. Must induce during moderate withdrawal (COWS ≥8-12) so partial agonism represents a net improvement.",
    explanationC: "Buprenorphine is NOT a pure antagonist — it IS an agonist (partial). If it were a pure antagonist like naloxone, it would provide NO opioid effect and could not treat cravings or withdrawal symptoms. Its partial agonism is what provides therapeutic benefit.",
    explanationD: "The naloxone component is NOT responsible for precipitated withdrawal during sublingual induction — naloxone has <5% sublingual bioavailability and is clinically INACTIVE when taken as directed. Precipitated withdrawal is entirely from BUPRENORPHINE itself displacing a full agonist with partial agonist activity.",
    examTip: "MAT comparison: BUPRENORPHINE: Partial μ-agonist, ceiling effect (safe), can prescribe office-based (X-waiver eliminated 2023), precipitated withdrawal risk if induced too early. METHADONE: Full μ-agonist, NO ceiling (overdose risk), QTc prolongation, OTP (opioid treatment program) dispensing only. NALTREXONE (Vivitrol): Pure μ-ANTAGONIST (extended-release IM monthly), requires 7-10 days opioid-free before initiation (otherwise precipitated withdrawal), no abuse potential, no respiratory depression. New approach: microinduction — very low-dose buprenorphine (0.25-0.5mg) introduced alongside full agonist, gradually increasing while tapering agonist — avoids precipitated withdrawal.",
